International Brief -- Riyad Bank:
   Protests in Saudi Arabia Fail
   To Halt Flotation Investors
They said flotation managers at the Consulting Center for
Finance and Investment in Riyadh are working around the clock
to speed the refund of the 7.7 billion riyals excess to
investors.
   A final share allocation will be awarded by the Ministry
of Commerce in the next few weeks.
   Diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
turnout of about 650,000 applicants was considered especially
high because some Muslim fundamentalists had urged the public
not to get involved with institutions charging interest.
Islamic law forbids the charging of interest in commercial
dealings.